Item: Political spectra <http://dbaron.org/log/2004-10#e20041002a>

Date: Sat Oct 02 07:42:00 UTC 2004
Author: David Baron

Since politics is (are?) on my mind lately, I want to point outan interesting site, PoliticalSurvey[1], which I first discovered when EricMeyer pointed it out[2] back in February.

It's interesting because it uses principalcomponent analysis[3] to derive the axes from the data, rather thantrying to pick axes in advance.  It's also interesting because the mostsignificant axis it finds is the traditional left/right axis, but thesecond axis isn't the libertarian/authoritarian axis that some assertshould be the second axis–rather, it's a pragmatic/idealisticaxis.

I've taken the survey twice, once in February and once today.  Myresults were similar:  I was in the left/pragmatic quadrant[4] bothtimes.  (In February, I was -4.08 on right/left and +5.17 onpragmatic/idealistic.  Today I was -3.63 on right/left and +4.65 onpragmatic/idealistic.)

[1] http://politics.beasts.org/
[2] http://www.meyerweb.com/eric/thoughts/2004/02/02/mapping-things-out/
[3] http://politics.beasts.org/rationale.shtml
[4] http://politics.beasts.org/scripts/eigenvectors****************************************
